Interview Questions

Q1. What is HashSet in Java?
-->HashSet is a class in the Java Collections Framework that implements the Set interface. It stores unique elements, does not maintain insertion order, and allows one null value. It is internally backed by a HashMap.

      Characteristics
      Stores unique elements only.
      Does not maintain insertion order.
      Allows one null element.
      Not synchronized.
      Provides fast insertion, deletion, and searching (average O(1)).
      
      Example:
      
      import java.util.*;
      
      public class Demo {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
      
              HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();
      
              set.add("Java");
              set.add("Python");
              set.add("Java");
      
              System.out.println(set);
          }
      }
      
      Possible Output
      
      [Java, Python]



Q2. How does HashSet ensure uniqueness of elements?
-->HashSet ensures uniqueness by using the hashCode() and equals() methods.

      Working Process
            Calls hashCode() to determine the bucket.
            If the bucket is empty, the element is added.
            If another element already exists in that bucket, equals() is used.
            If equals() returns true, the new element is considered a duplicate and is not added.
            If equals() returns false, the element is added.
            
            This guarantees that duplicate elements are not stored.



Q3. Does HashSet maintain insertion order?
-->No.

    HashSet does not maintain insertion order.
    
    The order of elements depends on their hash codes and internal hashing mechanism, so the output order may change.
    
    Example:
    
    HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();
    
    set.add("C");
    set.add("A");
    set.add("B");
    
    System.out.println(set);
    
    Possible Output
    [A, C, B]
    The order is not guaranteed.



Q4. What is the internal data structure used by HashSet?
-->HashSet is internally implemented using a HashMap.

      The elements of the HashSet are stored as keys in the HashMap.
      A dummy object (PRESENT) is used as the value.
      
      Internally:
      
      HashSet
      
      ↓
      
      HashMap
      
      ↓
      
      Bucket → Node → Node
      
      This design provides average O(1) performance for add, remove, and contains operations.




Q5. Can HashSet store null values? If yes, how many?
-->Yes.

      HashSet allows only one null value.
      
      Example:
      
      HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();
      
      set.add(null);
      set.add(null);
      
      System.out.println(set);
      
      Output
      
      [null]
      
      The second null is ignored because duplicates are not allowed.



Q6. Can HashSet store duplicate values? If not, what happens if we try?
-->No.

      HashSet does not allow duplicate values.
      
      If a duplicate element is added:
      
      The add() method returns false.
      The duplicate element is ignored.
      No exception is thrown.
      
      Example:
      
      HashSet<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();
      
      System.out.println(set.add(10));
      System.out.println(set.add(10));
      
      Output
      
      true
      false



Q7. Why does HashSet use hashCode() and equals() methods?
-->HashSet uses these methods to efficiently store and identify unique elements.

    hashCode()
    Determines the bucket where the element should be stored.
    equals()
    Compares two objects to determine whether they are equal.
    
    Without properly overriding these methods in custom classes, HashSet may incorrectly allow duplicate objects.
